soned in a camp where, after the onset of famine, very few children survived.The real significance of this episodic narrative is the way it shows, through the eyes of a child, the suppressed histories of China's invasion of Tibet. The author's matter-of-fact accounts cast the atrocities that he relays in stark relief. Remarkably, Naktsang lived to tell his tale. His book was published in 2007 in China, where it was a bestseller before the Chinese government banned it in 2010. It is the most reprinted modern Tibetan literary work. This translation makes a fascinating if painful period of modern Tibetan history accessible in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChildrenzChinazTibet Autonomous RegionvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh1 aCargill, Angus1 aLhamo, Sonam1 aLitzinger, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376385zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376385.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles